\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf4\sl276\slmult1\qj\aspalpha\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi708\rtlch\af2\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af8\langfe1042\hich\f2\fs22\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0 A pre-existing network can be partitioned in several ways. We thought about three different possibilities:}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf4\sl276\slmult1\qj\aspalpha\rtlch\af2\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af2\langfe1042\hich\f2\fs22\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\sl276\slmult1\qj\aspalpha\rtlch\af2\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af8\langfe1042\hich\f2\fs22\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0{\cf1 1. }}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0{\cf1\rtlch\ltrch\hich\b\loch\b Drop a secure network and create a new one}{\cf1 . This solution is not convenient and will not consist in separate a network but just in creating a new one. Moreover, we do not care about the shared resources which will be lost.}}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\aspalpha\ql\rtlch\af3\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af8\langfe1042\hich\f3\fs22\lang1036\loch\f3\fs22\lang1036 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\sl276\slmult1\qj\aspalpha\rtlch\af2\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af8\langfe1042\hich\f2\fs22\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0{\cf1 1.}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0{\cf4\rtlch\ltrch\hich\b\loch\b Drop a secure network and create new independent networks.}{\cf4  This solution is not convenient for users and does not consider shared resources that will be lost.}}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\sl276\slmult1\qj\aspalpha\rtlch\af2\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af2\langfe1042\hich\f2\fs22\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\sl276\slmult1\qj\aspalpha\rtlch\af2\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af8\langfe1042\hich\f2\fs22\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0 2. {\rtlch\ltrch\hich\b\loch\b Use the existing network in order to create, propagate and share a new session key for the new network before leaving the network and directly go to the new one}. It is actually the best solution and a fastest way for user to leave a network and directly
 start a new one. But users could encounter security issues with other members of the network that can read the traffic and steal the new key while it was sent to the members of the new network.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf3\sl276\slmult1\qj\aspalpha\rtlch\af2\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af8\langfe1042\hich\f2\fs22\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0 => In a merging, there is no problem.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\aspalpha\rtlch\af3\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af8\langfe1042\hich\f3\fs22\lang1036\loch\f3\fs22\lang1036 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0 => In a separating, there is a problem as explained above.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\sl276\slmult1\qj\aspalpha\rtlch\af2\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af2\langfe1042\hich\f2\fs22\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0 \line 2. {\cf4\rtlch\ltrch\hich\b\loch\b Use the existing network in order to create, propagate and share session keys for new networks, before leaving the former network and use only the new ones.}{\cf4  It is actually the fastest and most convenient solution for users, even if we are aware of a se
curity issue: during the propagation of a new session keys using the pre-existing network, users not belonging to the group creating the new sub-network are able to sniff the traffic and to potentially get the new key.}}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\aspalpha\ql\rtlch\af3\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af8\langfe1042\hich\f3\fs22\lang1036\loch\f3\fs22\lang1036 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\sl276\slmult1\qj\aspalpha\rtlch\af2\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af8\langfe1042\hich\f2\fs22\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0 3. {\rtlch\ltrch\hich\b\loch\b Use the existing network and use a group creating key to share a new key before leaving the network and directly go to the new one.} This case is pretty similar to the previous one. The group creating key protocol is just adding to the second idea in ord
er to reinforce the network security when the new key is distributed.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf3\aspalpha\ql\rtlch\af3\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af8\langfe1042\hich\f2\fs22\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0 => In a separating, the group creating key mechanism can solve the problem of 2.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf3\sl276\slmult1\qj\aspalpha\rtlch\af2\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af8\langfe1042\hich\f2\fs22\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0 => In a merging, the group creating key mechanisms is an overhead.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\aspalpha\ql\rtlch\af3\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af8\langfe1042\hich\f3\fs22\lang1036\loch\f3\fs22\lang1036 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\aspalpha\rtlch\af3\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af8\langfe1042\hich\f3\fs22\lang1036\loch\f3\fs22\lang1036 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\cf4\sl276\slmult1\qj\aspalpha\rtlch\af2\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af2\langfe1042\hich\f2\fs22\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0 3. {\rtlch\ltrch\hich\b\loch\b Use the existing network as well as a group key creation mechanism to obtain a new key before leaving the former network and use only the new one.} In this case, thanks to group key creation, only users belonging to a separating group can share the new k
ey, thus fixing the security problem described in the previous case.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\sl276\slmult1\qj\aspalpha\rtlch\af2\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af2\langfe1042\hich\f2\fs22\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0 \line \line }
