work.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\aspalpha\ql\rtlch\af3\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af8\langfe1042\hich\f3\fs22\lang1036\loch\f3\fs22\lang1036 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s8\aspalpha\ql\rtlch\af3\afs22\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af8\langfe1042\hich\f2\fs22\lang1033\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang1033\i0\b0 \tab {\cf4 Among these solutions, we chose the second one, but still considering the third idea as a possible way to improve security. The scenario we are considering is the following: in a already deployed spontaneous network, a subset of users decide to create the
ir own network, independent of the existing one. One user is delegated to fill a list of all users belonging to the new network; then a new session key, used to enable the new network, is created and propagated only to users belonging to the group, making 
them able to communicate independently of the former network. Other users are still able to use the pre-existing network. Since the previous network, available to all users, is used to share the new key, a malicious user not belonging to the separating gro
up could eavesdrop and get that key  fraudulently. Anyway we suppose a certain level of trust among }{\cf4\rtlch\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i all }{\cf4 users belonging to the original network, and that no classified or invaluable data are shared onto this kind of network.}}
